.TH "super" "1" "April 2026" ""
.SH NAME
super \(em process data with SuperSQL queries
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[B]\-c\f[R] \f[I]query\f[R]]
[\f[I]file\f[R] \&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]super\f[R] is the command\-line tool for interacting with and
managing SuperDB.
It is organized as a hierarchy of sub\-commands and can also be invoked
directly to run SuperSQL queries detached from any database storage
layer.
.PP
When invoked without a sub\-command, \f[B]super\f[R] executes the
SuperDB query engine against one or more input sources.
Inputs may be specified as command\-line paths, referenced within the
query itself (e.g., via a \f[B]from\f[R] operator or SQL FROM clause),
or read from standard input when the path argument is \f[CR]\-\f[R].
Inputs may be local file paths, HTTP, HTTPS, or S3 URLs.
.PP
When multiple input files are specified, they are processed in order as
if concatenated by a single \f[B]from\f[R] clause.
If no input is specified, the query receives a single \f[CR]null\f[R]
value, enabling use as a calculator or for standalone expressions.
.PP
Format detection is automatic for files with recognized extensions
(\f[CR].json\f[R], \f[CR].parquet\f[R], \f[CR].sup\f[R], etc.)
and for standard input.
The \f[CR]line\f[R] format cannot be auto\-detected and requires
explicit \f[CR]\-i line\f[R].
Parquet and CSUP require seekable input and cannot be read from standard
input.
.PP
Output is written to standard output by default.
When stdout is a terminal, the default output format is SUP; otherwise
it is BSUP.
These defaults may be overridden with \f[CR]\-f\f[R], \f[CR]\-s\f[R], or
\f[CR]\-S\f[R].
.PP
Runtime errors from queries do not halt execution.
Instead, they produce first\-class error values in the output stream,
interleaved with valid results.
These can be identified using the \f[B]is_error\f[R] function.
Fatal errors such as missing files cause immediate exit.
.PP
The \f[CR]\-C\f[R] flag compiles and displays the query in canonical
form without executing it, which is useful for understanding how
SuperSQL shortcuts are expanded.
